<p>Теперь пришло время для выбора мировоззрения. Каким будет Ваш 
персонаж -- добрым, злым или будет ни рыба ни мясо, то есть
нейтральный. Некоторые расы и профессии уже заведомо имеют какое-то
мировозрение 
(<a href='?section=getstart&name=alignment' target="_blank">
русский вариант текста</a>).
<pre class=sog_code>
Alignment defines character's creed, his behavior in various
situations and circumstances, and what is the most important to him
in his life.

-- good; such character has an "open soul", he recognizes and accepts
only bright and fair nature of people surrounding him; he always
tries to help those in need, provided it does not go against his own
principles (for chaotic), and does not break the law (for lawful);
good character appreciates and respects others, and he would not do
anything harmful to anyone.

-- evil; evil character lives for himself only, his own benefit is
of high importance to him.  He will not hesitate to hurt anyone, if
his interests require doing so.  He may kill, yet may help, if this
would enrich him, or allow to raise his social status.

-- neutral; such character is not openly generous (as good), but neither
is an egoist (as evil).  He lives primarily for Idea, which can be
anything, such as secret order, science, honor of uniform, money, or
whatever.

A note on "good vs. evil".  Evil character is not committed to
doing harm.  His "evilness" does only mean that he will do that
when needed.  Therefore, if good character finds out, say, from
'know alignment' that someone is evil and attacks that character,
he can no longer be called "good".  Such kind of deed would simply
be an indication of former good's cowardice.  That is, "evil alignment"
is not enough of reason for good character to start the confrontation,
as well as that evil character indeed had evil intents.  A single
thought cannot be justified as a crime, and no one can prove whether
it really did cross someone's mind or not.

You may be good, neutral, or evil.
Which alignment (G/N/E)? n
Now your character is neutral.
</pre>
<p>Мировозрение выбрано. Теперь выбирается место своего рождения в Shades of
Gray Realms. В Shades of Gray есть несколько мест, откуда можно начинать
игру. И при recall'е вы будете возвращаться именно в тот город, в котором
родились. Для вампиров и некромантов место рождения выбирать не придется -- у
них свое особое место рождения.
<pre class=sog_code>

You can pick one of six cities as your hometown: New Thalos and Midgaard are
all alignments. Ofcol is neutral only. Your hometown is where you will
recall to and is where the pit is to which your corpse will decay.
Everyone starts at mud school, which is connected to each of the hometowns.

[M]idgaard, [N]ew Thalos, [O]fcol?
</pre>
Дальше нам нужно выбрать свое отношение к социуму: lawful, neutral или chaotic
(<a href ='?section=getstart&name=ethos' target="_blank">русский вариант текста</a>).
<pre class=sog_code>

Ethos defines character's own valued principles and his attitude to
society, cultural traditions, and law.  There are three possibilities:

  -- lawful; such character respects and obeys all the laws and
traditions of society, no matter whether he benefits from it or not.
Laws prevail over his personal values and principles, and govern his
behavior.  Under any circumstances lawful character tries to find
the answers in traditions and law first, and if this fails, he may ask
people surrounding him, or find answers in himself.  He is always devoted
to serving the society, it's prosperity, and keeping it's traditions.
Lawful character will never ever break the law, even if it is meaningless,
or stupid (but such kind of thoughts never cross his mind); he will do
do it neither for himself, nor for his friends.

  -- chaotic; is the opposite of lawful.  Such character always and
everywhere is guided by his own beliefs and principles.  No matter what
he does, the key factor is his own benefit, not his friend's, group-
mate's, or anyone's else; he does not care about society either.  However,
being chaotic does not mean that such character is committed to break the
law, or go against it, still he would not doubt doing so, but only if
the law contradicts with his own principles or interests.  It should be
noted that character who's life goes as "his left (or right) heel wants"
is not really a chaotic, but simply does not have any stand, and he
actually should think about it.

  -- neutral; is somewhat a middle of two extremities: serving the society
and serving himself; uncomplaining acceptance of the laws and persistent
commitment to his own ideals only.  Society as a whole does not matter
much for neutral character, but people (and other creatures) who form
it do.  They might be his friends, group-mates, or might confess the same
idea or region as he does.  Neutral character may break the law, if he, or
his friend needs it, or give up on his own interests for the sake his deed
(order, guild, etc).

What ethos do you want, (L/N/C) <type help for more info>?
</pre>
